import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['job'] = data['job'].astype('category')
    data['job_count'] = data.groupby('job')['count'].transform('sum')
    data = data.drop_duplicates(subset=['job'])
    data = data.sort_values(by='job_count', ascending=False)
    ax = sns.barplot(x='job', y='job_count', data=data)
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('What is the most common job title in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='ignore')
    ax = sns.lineplot(x='year', y='count', hue='job', data=data)
    ax.set(xlabel='Year', ylabel='Job Title Count')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('How has the distribution of job titles changed over time?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='ignore')
    top_jobs = data.groupby('job').sum().sort_values(by='count', ascending=False).head(10).index.tolist()
    data = data[data['job'].isin(top_jobs)]
    data = data.groupby(['job', 'sex']).sum().reset_index()
    chart = sns.barplot(x='job', y='count', hue='sex', data=data)
    chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        chart.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('What is the gender distribution for the top 10 job titles?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='ignore')
    women_percentage = data[data['sex'] == 'women']['perc'].sum()
    men_percentage = data[data['sex'] == 'men']['perc'].sum()
    gender_percentage = pd.DataFrame({'gender': ['women', 'men'], 'percentage': [women_percentage, men_percentage]})
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    ax = sns.barplot(x='gender', y='percentage', data=gender_percentage)
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.PercentFormatter(xmax=1, decimals=0))
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    plt.xlabel('Gender')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage')
    plt.title('What is the percentage of women in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

    plt.xlabel('Job Title Count')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title('What is the distribution of job title count?', wrap=True)
    return plt;
